Hello Bittensor community, I am mostly working on subnets, miner and validator tooling, and data and training pipelines.
I worked with the Bittensor SDK and Subtensor, Python and PyTorch, FastAPI services, evaluation and weights logic, and monitoring and deployment on Kubernetes.
I want to contribute examples for subnet templates, validator scoring and reward modeling, and production operations, and discuss here.

We are ready to take our project - _the real-time dtaostats.io runtime simulator_ - to the next phase! And I still need the help of someone speaking rust, but now for a far more localized, focused problem.

I explicitly also welcome the job seekers who reached out to me before, to read this and consider whether this next phase we're in, matches their level of skill and ambition.

Where we stand:
- we can build a tweaked runtime: `cargo build -p node-subtensor-runtime --release --features metadata-hash,try-runtime`
- we can run the tweaked runtime against chain state: `try-runtime --runtime /.../node_subtensor_runtime.compact.wasm follow-chain --uri ws://0:9944` 
- we can process log output of the tweaked runtime and write files using some simple script
- in the tweaked runtime in `pallets/subtensor/src/coinbase/block_step.rs:block_step()` we can invoke `run_coinbase()` N times to make N steps per block

In essence, this is good enough for what we want to build. So this defines the context and makes the remaining project a more straightforward coding exercise.

The problem we run into is that `run_coinbase()` is extremely slow, 140 ms/invocation. For now we can skip the last stage of it (distributing coins to wallets), making it 40ms/invocation, which is still a lot.

We see various ways to speed this up:
- use native float or int types instead of U96F32 fixed point (we don't care about cross platform deterministic execution)
- use plain arrays instead of BTreeMap
- let `run_coinbase()` perform multiple steps on local variables, saving many round-trips to StorageMaps
- eliminate some expensive calls, replacing them with cost-effective (local) approximations
- increase the simulated emission (e.g. simulate 10 blocks at a time by emitting 10 tao instead of 1)

In total this should get execution time per block to <1 ms, allowing us to simulate multiple days per 12 seconds, giving real-time insights into subnet status. We already did some experiments and it seems that eliminating BTreeMap and using native types isn't problematic; it just takes time without the proper IDE or rust experience.
